  49: and precautions. 
  50: Evidence base and study architecture
  51: This report prioritizes the core SURPASS publications, the pre-approval statistical review from the FDA, the
  52: current U.S. prescribing information, the product information from the EMA, and higher-quality systematic
  53: and network meta-analyses. All pivotal SURPASS studies were sponsored by Eli Lilly and Company
  54: . The
  55: program was designed to test tirzepatide across the type 2 diabetes treatment continuum: diet and exercise
  56: alone, metformin background therapy, metformin plus SGLT2 inhibitor therapy, high-cardiovascular-risk
  57: populations on oral agents, and patients already using basal insulin. Primary eﬃcacy endpoints were
  58: usually change in HbA1c at 40 or 52 weeks, with body weight, HbA1c target attainment, fasting glucose, and
  59: selected metabolic markers as key secondary endpoints. 
  60: Methodologically, the program mixes double-blind placebo-controlled trials and open-label active-
  61: comparator trials. That matters: open-label designs may inﬂuence symptom reporting, treatment
  62: discontinuation, and behavioral co-interventions, although HbA1c itself is an objective endpoint. Another
  63: architectural point is comparator selection. The most important direct GLP-1 receptor agonist comparison,
  64: SURPASS-2, used semaglutide 1 mg once weekly. Higher semaglutide doses are now used in current
  65: practice, including 2 mg weekly for type 2 diabetes; therefore some modern tirzepatide-versus-semaglutide
  66: comparisons rely on indirect evidence rather than direct head-to-head randomization. 
