 592: Glycemic eﬃcacy
 593: Tirzepatide’s glycemic eﬃcacy is robust across every major comparison that matters clinically. Against
 594: placebo monotherapy in SURPASS-1, the highest dose reduced HbA1c by 2.07% from a baseline around
 595: 7.9%, with 87% to 92% of patients reaching HbA1c <7%. Against semaglutide 1 mg in SURPASS-2, superiority
 596: was statistically demonstrated at all doses for HbA1c, with the largest eﬀect at 15 mg. Against basal insulin
 597: strategies in SURPASS-3 and SURPASS-4, tirzepatide lowered HbA1c by roughly another 0.6% to 1.1% beyond
 598: degludec or glargine. And in SURPASS-6, when the practical decision was “weekly incretin intensiﬁcation”
 599: versus “basal-bolus intensiﬁcation,” tirzepatide again won, with a pooled mean HbA1c diﬀerence of nearly 1
 600: percentage point and a much larger proportion of patients reaching HbA1c <7%. 
 601: Clinically, the target-attainment results are as impressive as the mean-change results. In SURPASS-2, HbA1c
 602: <7% was achieved by 82%, 86%, and 86% with tirzepatide 5, 10, and 15 mg, compared with 79% for
 603: semaglutide 1 mg; HbA1c <5.7% was achieved by 27%, 40%, and 46% versus 19%. In SURPASS-4, the
 604: week-52 rates were more widely separated: HbA1c <7% in 81%, 88%, and 91% versus 51% with glargine;
 605: HbA1c <5.7% in 23%, 33%, and 43% versus 3%. In SURPASS-5, HbA1c <7% occurred in 85% to 90% of
 606: tirzepatide-treated patients versus 34% with placebo despite background basal insulin. Across the earlier
 607: SURPASS program, JAMA’s summary of the program-level experience reported that 81% to 97% of
 608: participants achieved HbA1c <7% and 23% to 62% achieved HbA1c <5.7%, depending on dose and trial
 609: context. 
 610: The time-course also matters. From the trial ﬁgures, HbA1c curves generally separate within roughly 8 to 12
 611: weeks, then stabilize at lower levels by 24 to 40 weeks, while higher tirzepatide doses preserve separation
 612: thereafter. Weight curves often keep diverging after glycemic curves have begun to stabilize. That pattern is
 613: clearest in SURPASS-2 and SURPASS-3, and SURPASS-1 explicitly noted that weight loss had not plateaued by
 614: week 40. In SURPASS-4, durability is unusually well documented: at 104 weeks, HbA1c still averaged 6.43%,
 615: 6.13%, and 6.11% with tirzepatide 5, 10, and 15 mg versus 7.47% with glargine. This is partly an inference
 616: from trial trajectory graphs, but it is well supported by the long-term follow-up data. 
 617: Weight loss and cardiometabolic eﬀects
 618: For many clinicians, tirzepatide’s diﬀerentiator is not just HbA1c but the size and consistency of its weight
 619: eﬀect in people with diabetes. In SURPASS-1, tirzepatide produced up to 9.5 kg weight loss, roughly 11.0%
 620: of baseline body weight. In SURPASS-2, the eﬀect was dose-dependent and clearly stronger than
 621: semaglutide 1 mg: at 40 weeks, weight loss was 7.6, 9.3, and 11.2 kg with tirzepatide versus 5.7 kg with
 622: semaglutide, with corresponding eﬃcacy-estimand losses of 8.5%, 11.0%, and 13.1% versus 6.7%. In
 623: SURPASS-3, the highest dose produced about 12.9 kg loss, around 13.9% of baseline weight, whereas
 624: insulin degludec caused gain. In SURPASS-5 and SURPASS-6, tirzepatide continued to reduce weight despite
 625: background insulin, a setting in which weight gain is usually expected. 
 626: Target-based weight outcomes reinforce that impression. In SURPASS-2, at least 15% body-weight loss
 627: occurred in 15%, 24%, and 36% of tirzepatide-treated patients versus 8% with semaglutide. In SURPASS-5,
 628: the rates of at least 5%, 10%, and 15% loss were 48% to 72%, 21% to 42%, and 7% to 24% with tirzepatide
 629: versus 6%, 1%, and 0% with placebo. In SURPASS-6, body-weight loss of at least 5%, 10%, and 15% was
 630: achieved by 62% to 78%, 32% to 57%, and 13% to 37%, respectively, despite ongoing basal insulin. These are
