 640: not trivial cosmetic diﬀerences; they shift the likely metabolic phenotype of the patient, aﬀect insulin
 641: resistance, and often inﬂuence treatment adherence and patient preference. 
 642: Cardiometabolic laboratory eﬀects were directionally favorable, though usually secondary or exploratory. In
 643: SURPASS-2, tirzepatide lowered triglycerides and VLDL cholesterol more than semaglutide and raised HDL
 644: cholesterol more, while total cholesterol and LDL cholesterol did not diﬀer signiﬁcantly. Systolic blood
 645: pressure fell by 4.8 to 6.5 mm Hg with tirzepatide versus 3.6 mm Hg with semaglutide, and diastolic blood
 646: pressure fell by 1.9 to 2.9 mm Hg versus 1.0 mm Hg. Pulse rose modestly and similarly with tirzepatide and
 647: semaglutide, generally by about 2 to 3 beats per minute by week 40. In SURPASS-4 and SURPASS-CVOT,
 648: triglycerides and systolic blood pressure also moved modestly in favor of tirzepatide. 
