 907: Safety and tolerability
 908: The adverse-event proﬁle is recognizably incretin-like and dose-dependent. In the pooled placebo-
 909: controlled adult type 2 diabetes trials used in the U.S. label, nausea occurred in 12%, 15%, and 18% with
 910: tirzepatide 5, 10, and 15 mg versus 4% with placebo; diarrhea in 12%, 13%, and 17% versus 9%; vomiting in
 911: 5%, 5%, and 9% versus 2%; constipation in 6%, 6%, and 7% versus 1%; and dyspepsia in 8%, 8%, and 5%
 912: versus 3%. Gastrointestinal adverse reactions overall occurred in 37.1%, 39.6%, and 43.6% of tirzepatide-
 913: treated patients versus 20.4% with placebo. Discontinuation due speciﬁcally to GI adverse events was 3.0%,
 914: 5.4%, and 6.6% versus 0.4% with placebo, and most nausea, vomiting, and diarrhea clustered during dose
 915: escalation and then decreased over time. 
 916: The direct-comparator trials sharpen the clinical picture. In SURPASS-2, nausea was not clearly higher than
 917: with semaglutide 1 mg, but diarrhea, vomiting, and decreased appetite trended upward with higher
 918: tirzepatide doses. In SURPASS-4, nausea rose from 12% at 5 mg to 23% at 15 mg versus 2% with glargine;
 919: diarrhea rose from 13% to 22% versus 4%; and treatment discontinuation due to any adverse event was 9%
 920: to 11% versus 5%. In SURPASS-5, treatment-emergent nausea was 12.9%, 17.6%, and 18.3% versus 2.5%
 921: with placebo; diarrhea 12.1%, 12.6%, and 20.8% versus 10.0%; vomiting 6.9%, 7.6%, and 12.5% versus 2.5%;
 922: and discontinuation due to adverse events 6.0%, 8.4%, and 10.8% versus 2.5%. In SURPASS-6, pooled
 923: gastrointestinal adverse events occurred in 42.3% with tirzepatide and 8.6% with insulin lispro, but serious
 924: adverse events were actually less frequent with tirzepatide than with lispro. 
 925: Hypoglycemia is where tirzepatide’s safety proﬁle becomes context-dependent. In monotherapy or oral-
 926: drug settings, clinically signiﬁcant hypoglycemia is rare: the label reports 0% with tirzepatide monotherapy
 927: versus 1% with placebo for blood glucose <54 mg/dL, and SURPASS-1 reported no clinically signiﬁcant or
 928: severe hypoglycemia. But when background insulin or sulfonylureas are present, risk rises. In SURPASS-5,
 929: hypoglycemia <54 mg/dL occurred in 14.2% to 19.3% versus 12.5% with placebo, and three episodes of
 930: severe hypoglycemia occurred across the 10 mg and 15 mg groups. In contrast, in SURPASS-6 the
 931: comparison was favorable: severe hypoglycemia occurred in 0.4% of tirzepatide-treated patients versus
 932: 4.2% of insulin-lispro-treated patients, and clinically signiﬁcant or severe events occurred at 0.4 versus 4.4
 933: events per patient-year. That diﬀerence is one of the strongest practical arguments for using tirzepatide
 934: before escalating to basal-bolus insulin in suitable patients. 
 935: Pancreatitis, gallbladder disease, cardiovascular events, and injection-site reactions deserve separate
 936: attention because they shape monitoring and counseling. The U.S. label states that tirzepatide has not been
 937: studied in patients with a prior history of pancreatitis and warns to discontinue if pancreatitis is suspected.
